Deputy President William Ruto&rsquo;s arguments on pertinent issues are no different from an illiterate man&rsquo;s, NASA co-principal Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula has said.He spoke on Friday in Kanduyi, Bungoma county, when he met Ford Kenya aspirants who lost in the primaries.&ldquo;I wonder what he was doing in class,&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula said.He cited Ruto&rsquo;s arguments on the World Bank and IMF advisory on foreign lending, saying the DP&rsquo;s dismissal of the report showed he has no grasp of the issues.&ldquo;How can a person who went to school start arguing and rubbishing bodies like the World Bank and IMF?&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula asked.He said the country&rsquo;s over-borrowing is a risk and promised that a NASA government would recheck the borrowing.The Ford-K leader said Ruto does not have the moral authority to speak ill about NASA leaders as his source of wealth is questionable.&ldquo;Let him stop saying lies about us because we are going to tell Kenyans lots of truth about them,&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula said.The Jubilee administration has failed to run the country but only works under pressure and protests, he said.Wetang&rsquo;ula defended NASA&rsquo;s intention to run a parallel tallying centre, saying the coalition wants to ensure the polls are not rigged.It is not illegal to run a parallel tally and Jubilee opposing the move shows they plan to rig polls, he said.Wetang&rsquo;ula said NASA has strategies to protect its 10 million votes.Deputy President William Ruto&rsquo;s arguments on pertinent issues are no different from an illiterate man&rsquo;s, NASA co-principal Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula has said.He spoke on Friday in Kanduyi, Bungoma county, when he met Ford Kenya aspirants who lost in the primaries.&ldquo;I wonder what he was doing in class,&rdquo; Wetang&rsquo;ula said.He cited Ruto&rsquo;s arguments on the World Bank and IMF advisory on foreign lending, saying the DP&rsquo;s dismissal of the report showed he has no grasp of the issues.&ldquo;